sec.p:
A linear neighborhood logistic regression (LNNL) was the first model that we implemented in an attempt to cluster a new sample, the algorithm computes the Euclidean distance between the sample and all the training ones:
\begin{equation*}
d\left(x_{i}, x_{j}\right)=\sqrt{\sum_{f=1}^{F}\left(x_{i}^{f}-x_{j}^{f}\right)^{2}}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

It turns out, we then just vote based on the majority of the k nearest neighbors for the class label:
\begin{equation*}
\hat{y}=\arg _{c \in C} \max _{i \in N_{k}(x)} 1\left(y_{i}=c\right)
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

In order to perform classification of fetal states, we adopted the SVM machine learning technique to build optimal separation surfaces. To every binary classification problem, we applied the solving of:
\begin{equation*}
\min \frac{1}{2}\vertw\vert^{2} \text { s.t. } y_{i}\left(w. x_{i}+b\right) \geq 1
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

For non-linearly separable data, we introduced slack variables $\xi_{i}$ and optimized:
\begin{equation*}
\min \frac{1}{2}\vertw\vert^{2}+C \sum_{i} \xi_{i}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

We implemented the RBF kernel to capture non-linear patterns:
\begin{equation*}
K\left(x_{i}, x_{j}\right)=\exp \left(-\gamma\left\vertx_{i}-x_{j}\right\vert^{2}\right.
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

We used Random Forest to construct a decision trees ensemble to enhance robustness of classifications and interpretability. All trees were fit using bootstrap samples of the training set and optimal splits were found by minimising Gini impurity:
\begin{equation*}
\text { Gini }=1-\sum_{c=1}^{c} p_{c}^{2}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

Predictions were made by majority voting across all trees:
\begin{equation*}
\hat{y}=\arg _{c \in C} \max _{t=1}^{T} 1\left(h_{t}(x)=c\right)
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
